# Project Memory — Example

Copy this to your agent's project-level memory location (e.g.
`~/.claude/projects/<project-path>/memory/MEMORY.md`) and adapt the sections
to your project. This file is loaded at the start of every session, giving
your agent persistent context across session boundaries.

Keep it concise. This file is consumed on every session start — bloat here
costs tokens on every interaction. Per-commit detail belongs in checkpoint
files, not here.

---

## Project
<!-- One-line description. What is this project? -->

## Owner
<!-- Who owns the project, where the repo lives, key paths. -->

## Communication Protocol
<!-- Define your shorthand signals here. Example:
- y = yes/approved
- t = continue
- d = discuss before proceeding
- p = Popperian falsification pass
-->

## Key Decisions
<!-- Confirmed architectural and design decisions. One line each.
These prevent agents from relitigating settled questions. Example:
- Stack: FastAPI + PostgreSQL + HTMX
- Auth: JWT tokens, no session cookies
- Testing: pytest, minimum 80% coverage on new code
-->

## Current State
<!-- What has been done, what's the latest commit, test count, pending items.
Keep this under 40 lines. Update every session. Example:
- 127 tests passing
- HEAD: abc1234 — added user registration endpoint
- Auth module complete, payment integration in progress
-->

## Strategic Gaps
<!-- Known issues that aren't current blockers but will become pressing at
specific triggers. Include the trigger condition so agents know when to act.
Example:
- Rate limiting: not needed at current scale. TRIGGER: before public launch.
- Database migration tooling: manual SQL currently. TRIGGER: when schema
  changes exceed 3 per week.
-->

## Infrastructure Not Yet Built
<!-- Deferred work with clear trigger conditions. Similar to strategic gaps
but for missing components rather than design issues. -->

## What Remains
<!-- High-level roadmap of remaining work. Not a task list — that's what
Open Brain's task system is for. This is the big picture. -->

## Session Tips
<!-- Practical notes for agents starting a session. What to read first,
common pitfalls, environment setup notes. Example:
- Read ACTION_QUEUE.md on every session start
- Run `ob session-context --agent cc` for pending tasks
- Keep sessions short — commit at each milestone
-->
